The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Business Briefs
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                   Business Briefs
                              
	 Mumbai, Sept. 9: Reliance Industries Ltd (RIL) will set up wholly owned subsidiaries in London and Singapore to tap the market for petroleum products in these countries. While London-headquartered Reliance Global Energy Services Ltd will be led by Peter Ward, Reliance Global Energy Services Singapore will be headed by Michael Ng.                            
	 New Delhi, Sept. 9: A Mauritius-based equity fund has acquired a 17 per cent stake in BPL Mobile for $80 million. The selloff will help BPL Mobile raise funds for expansion and pick up a stake in Mumbai-based Loop Telecom. Loop Telecom recently got a pan-India mobile licence and paid a licence fee of Rs 1,400 crore.                            
	 New Delhi, Sept. 9: The government will soon issue guidelines for imposing safeguard duties to restrict the surge in the imports of commodities from countries with which India has signed free trade agreements.                            
	 New Delhi, Sept. 9: The National Stock Exchange has ruled out listing of the bourse and said it would launch interest rate and currency futures in pairs other than the dollar when it gets approval from Sebi.                             
	 Mumbai, Sept. 9: Idea Cellulars open offer for acquiring 20 per cent equity shares in BK Modi-led Spice Communications will open on September 17 and close on October 6.                            
	 New Delhi, Sept. 9: Tech Mahindra has bagged a five-year $250-million system integration order from a US-based telecom company. Tech Mahindra will provide all the managed services as well as the systems consolidation job for the US firm.                            
	 New Delhi, Sept. 9: ONGC has suffered a setback in its efforts to pick up a 25 per cent stake in the Satpayev oil field in the Caspian Sea after Kazakhstan backtracked on its commitment.                                                                                                                       
